<!-- ── Slide 2: Story Clustering ── -->
<div class="sl" id="s2">
<div class="inner">
  <div class="eyebrow"><div class="eyebrow-dot"></div>Stage 02 — Story Clustering</div>
  <div class="h2">TF-IDF Cosine Similarity → <span>Same Event, Multiple Outlets</span></div>
  <p class="lead">Before any bias analysis runs, articles covering the same event must be grouped. Cross-outlet variance only reveals bias when comparing BBC and Fox on the <em style="color:#fff;font-style:normal">same story</em>, not different stories.</p>

  <div class="chain">
    <div class="cnode">28 articles</div><div class="carrow">→</div>
    <div class="cnode">TF-IDF matrix (N×5000)</div><div class="carrow">→</div>
    <div class="cnode">cosine sim &gt; 0.35</div><div class="carrow">→</div>
    <div class="cnode hl">story groups [ ]</div><div class="carrow">→</div>
    <div class="cnode">bias engine per group</div>
  </div>

  <div class="cards">
    <div class="card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')">
      <div class="card-icon">📐</div><div class="card-title">TF-IDF Vectorization</div>
      <div class="card-sub">scikit-learn TfidfVectorizer on article titles</div>
      <div class="card-detail">TfidfVectorizer(max_features=5000) converts each title to a sparse term-weight vector. Rare discriminative words get higher IDF weight. Stop words auto-removed. Result: N×5000 sparse matrix ready for cosine comparison.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')">
      <div class="card-icon">📏</div><div class="card-title">Custom TF-IDF + Cosine</div>
      <div class="card-sub">Built from scratch — tf × log((1+N)/(1+df)) + 1</div>
      <div class="card-detail">Custom implementation: tf × idf for each word, L2-normalized. cosine_similarity = dot product of two normalized vectors. Threshold 0.35 tuned to prevent false groupings. Also uses Jaccard keyword similarity as secondary signal.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')">
      <div class="card-icon">🧬</div><div class="card-title">SentenceTransformers</div>
      <div class="card-sub">all-MiniLM-L6-v2 semantic matching</div>
      <div class="card-detail">For cross-feed analysis: encode(texts) → 384-dim dense embeddings. Semantic grouping catches paraphrased titles TF-IDF misses. "Economy shrinks" and "GDP contracts" cluster correctly because their embeddings are close in vector space.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')">
      <div class="card-icon">📊</div><div class="card-title">Cross-Outlet Variance</div>
      <div class="card-sub">Which of the 17 parameters diverges most?</div>
      <div class="card-detail">For each story group, compute variance of each of 17 parameter scores across all outlets. most_divergent = max(variances, key=variances.get). Example: "BBC and Fox agree on facts but diverge on framing_bias by 48 points."</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="infobox"><strong>Why this matters:</strong> A single-article bias score tells you one outlet's stance. A cross-outlet group score tells you <em>where journalism diverges</em> — the specific bias dimension that separates responsible reporting from slanted reporting on the same event.</div>

  <div class="badge-row">
    <div class="badge-label">NLP</div>
    <div class="badges"><span class="badge">scikit-learn TF-IDF</span><span class="badge">cosine_similarity</span><span class="badge">SentenceTransformers</span><span class="badge">all-MiniLM-L6-v2</span><span class="badge">Jaccard keyword sim</span><span class="badge">GDELT tone API</span></div>
  </div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- ── Slide 3: BERT + PE ── -->
<div class="sl" id="s3">
<div class="inner">
  <div class="eyebrow"><div class="eyebrow-dot"></div>Stage 03 — Deep NLP</div>
  <div class="h2">4-Level Positional Encoding → <span>BERT Contextual Embeddings</span></div>
  <p class="lead">The same word "crisis" carries a different bias signal depending on where it appears. A 4-level hierarchical position weight system encodes this <em style="color:#fff;font-style:normal">before</em> BERT processes the article.</p>

  <div class="two-col">
    <div>
      <div class="section-label">Level 1 — Token position weight within sentence</div>
      <div class="cards" style="grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:8px;margin:10px 0">
        <div class="card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')" style="padding:14px">
          <div class="card-title" style="font-size:12px">pos:1–2 · 3.2× weight</div><div class="card-sub">Early-sentence position. Editors front-load the narrative frame. Every charged word at start = amplified signal.</div>
          <div class="card-detail">Tokens 1-2 in a sentence receive 3.2× multiplier. BERT encodes left-context dependency — "Economy crisis" → "crisis" gets higher framing_bias weight because "Economy" established the economic frame.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')" style="padding:14px">
          <div class="card-title" style="font-size:12px">pos:3–5 · 1× baseline</div><div class="card-sub">Mid-sentence position. Standard weight. Often carries supporting factual claims or elaboration.</div>
          <div class="card-detail">Mid-sentence tokens carry standard 1× weight. Frequently contain factual assertions, data citations, or bridging language. Lower editorial control means lower bias weight.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')" style="padding:14px">
          <div class="card-title" style="font-size:12px">pos:6+ · 0.8× reduced</div><div class="card-sub">Late-sentence position. Supporting context. Often attribution, quotes, or subordinate clauses.</div>
          <div class="card-detail">Late-sentence tokens (position 6+) get 0.8× weight. Attribution and quotes live here — reducing weight prevents quoted speech from inflating bias score unfairly.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')" style="padding:14px">
          <div class="card-title" style="font-size:12px">ALL-CAPS detection +15</div><div class="card-sub">Title case analysis. ALL-CAPS headline adds +15 pts to sensationalism parameter directly.</div>
          <div class="card-detail">Uppercase detection applied to headline tokens specifically. ALL-CAPS title is a strong sensationalism signal independent of word content. Flat +15 added to sensationalism score before other keyword scoring.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="section-label">Level 4 — Structural unit weight</div>
      <div class="cards" style="grid-template-columns:1fr;gap:8px;margin:10px 0">
        <div class="card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')" style="padding:14px"><div class="card-title" style="font-size:12px">Headline → 3.5× weight</div><div class="card-sub">Strongest signal. Encodes entire editorial angle in ~10 words.</div><div class="card-detail">Headline_bias checks (a) sensational word count AND (b) cosine similarity between headline vector and body vector. Low headline-body overlap = clickbait mismatch. Both signals combined into single headline_bias score.</div></div>
        <div class="card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')" style="padding:14px"><div class="card-title" style="font-size:12px">Lede paragraph → 2× weight</div><div class="card-sub">Sets the reader's frame. Second-highest editorial agency.</div><div class="card-detail">First paragraph establishes what kind of story this is. Every keyword hit in P1 is amplified 2× before contributing to parameter scores. Framing_bias parameter is especially sensitive to lede language.</div></div>
        <div class="card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')" style="padding:14px"><div class="card-title" style="font-size:12px">Body paragraphs → 1× base</div><div class="card-sub">Standard weight. Factual reporting layer.</div><div class="card-detail">All 17 parameters applied at standard 1× weight. Usually more neutral register — editors have less control over paragraph-level language than headlines.</div></div>
        <div class="card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('open')" style="padding:14px"><div class="card-title" style="font-size:12px">Closing paragraph → 0.7×</div><div class="card-sub">Agenda_setting monitors closing for urgency language.</div><div class="card-detail">Closing often contains summary, prediction, or call-to-action. agenda_setting parameter specifically watches here for "must act now", "wake up call" despite reduced structural weight.</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="infobox"><strong>BERT sentence embeddings:</strong> encode(sentences) → 384-dim dense vectors via all-MiniLM-L6-v2. Captures negation, sarcasm, and synonymy that keyword lists miss. "Not corrupt" ≠ "corrupt" in embedding space. Used for framing_bias cross-outlet semantic distance calculation.</div>

  <div class="badge-row">
    <div class="badge-label">NLP</div>
    <div class="badges"><span class="badge">SentenceTransformers</span><span class="badge">all-MiniLM-L6-v2</span><span class="badge">TextBlob sentiment</span><span class="badge">positional weight matrix</span><span class="badge">headline-body cosine</span></div>
  </div>
</div>
</div>

